they saw no purpose or whatever, and they had their established publishing outlets, and they were different.

And the architecture people, that was cool.
Do you think the, generally faculty,
are aware and supported of a university press?
You can say that generically for any university or Texas A&M University.
I think it's a curious thing.
I think that many faculty are more sympathetic and more aware of a university press at another institution than they are of their own.
That can be almost a... That's why I asked the question.
I think so too.
Well, they don't, I don't know exactly why this is.
They always, the profit is never appreciated at home.
That's right.
And I think that applies right across the board for, it was my experience at California and LSU also, that the likelihood was for a faculty person to
Trying to publish elsewhere, right, because they sense that if you have to go publish on your own, it's less prestigious.
Yeah, well, it's just a house organ that just cranks out stuff because it can't get accepted anywhere else.
And originally, university presses struggled under this a lot.
And in fact, if you look at Cal, the history there
You hear people saying this is the reason that they started the thing.
Certain departments couldn't get, they didn't have the publishing outlets, and they wanted some way to get their stuff available.
And that was one of the main reasons for a university press.
What do you think a university press, a Texas A&M university press,
Well, I think it demonstrated the coming of age of Texas A&M University as a full-fledged, as not just a technical school or a military academy.
This, I think, a university press, certainly in my time, a university press was
indication of the maturity and sophistication and competence and all the rest of the institution.
And during the, from the 50s through the 70s anyway, a lot of university presses were started.
There were lots of them.
Just look at Texas.
I mean, a whole lot of things got started just inside the state, but that went on all over the country.
Are they going to...
The responsibility of the university press was to academic excellence, to providing
an outlet for material that didn't necessarily appeal to a wide audience, that it was important for a university press to publish material that was for scholars.
I don't think that's the way it is anymore.
I think the line between commercial presses and university presses has become almost obliterated.
It's very hard to distinguish
I mean, that book we were talking about the other day, the LSU Confederacy of Dunces.
I mean, that a university press should publish that book.
Many places would have refused to consider that years ago.
Now, almost any would love it to happen.
And this is partly because the kind of support
that was originally provided to university presses has become less and less and less.
Marketplace is directing the university press.
Yes, and that's not always the best.
In many ways, it's bad.
Top stuff gets the lead.
And this is where Frank bridged that.
I mean, got over that pop stuff by doing those picture books.
I mean, some of those picture books are perfect examples.
I mean, he was able to do those and not compromise, or not seem to compromise.
